The `switch` statement selects one of many code blocks based on a value. Java 14+ introduced switch *expressions* with arrow (`->`) syntax that return a value.

**Classic switch** uses `case:`, `break`, and `default:`.

**Switch expression** (Java 14+):
```java
String day = switch (n) {
    case 1 -> "Monday";
    case 2 -> "Tuesday";
    default -> "Other";
};
```

Switch expressions eliminate fall-through bugs and can be used directly in assignments.

examples.code:
int day = 3;
String name = switch (day) {
    case 1 -> "Monday";
    case 2 -> "Tuesday";
    case 3 -> "Wednesday";
    default -> "Other";
};
System.out.println(name);

